Creating a food delivery app.
Things required:
  1.Restaurant class----id, name, address, vector<Menu Item>menu (Model class)
  2.Menu Item class-code for item, name, price --Model class as it has no functionalities.
Restaurant has menu items(has-a) relationship. 
**Menu item can exist independently. For say in an particular area when we can check for a particular dish, it doesnt depend on Restaurant.
But for this case lets assume Menu Item is dependent on Restaurant.
(Composition relationship).

We will have various Restaurants in the app. Some actively yake orders, some dont, some new Restaurants are added some are removed etc.
So to manage Restaurants we need a Restaurant Manager which does certian operations like CRUD, searching Restaurants by location.

Here Restaurant and RestaurantManager have aggregation relationship(Composition).
--Restaurant can exist independently. RestaurantManager must be a singleton.
3.RestaurantManager--vector<Restaurant>restaurants, addRes();, searchByLoc(loc);

Restaurant Manager acts as the one where anyone can indirectly contact Restaurants. By this we can kee things loosely coupled.
Manager objects are preffered in such cases.

4.User class --id, name,address,cart (Model class)
5.Cart class-- Restaurant res, vector<Menu Items>items, total price, addToCart(item), clear(), isEmpty()
  Cart and Restaurant can exist independently so simple association relationship.
  Cart has menu Items.
  Cart cannot exist independentlywithout user. So they have Composition realtionship

6.Payment Strategy (abstract class)--pay()
  It will have UPI,NET Banking, CC (Strategy Design Pattern)

 7. Order --id, Restaurant res, vector<Menu Item>Items, User user, PaymentStrategy ps, getType()
 -- This can be an abstract class as getType of order is an pure virtual method.
 -- Order has a user(simple association)
 --Order has Restaurant, Has PaymentStrategy, has user, has Menu Items.
-- inheritance for the getType() of orders. 1.Delivery order and 2.Pickup order 

To make more scalable we can use Factory method pattern for order, this will create orders.
8.Order Factory(abstract class)--creates order(), 
  CreateOrder()--1.Now Order Factory 2. Schedule Order Factory.(These two override createOrder())
  -- Both of them can do Delivery Order anD Pickup Order
  --Order Factory has a order.(We dont draw this in UML as relationship is shown through concrete classes to concrete product)
    
 9.Order Manager class- vector<order>orders (one to many relationship between Order manager and orders.), addOrder(order)
   --Order Manager has an aggregation relationship with order (one to many)
   --Singleton

10.Notification Service class- Notify(order)

11.Tomato class --Acts as Orchestrator , intercats with all the classes and gives an single point of contact to the client
 --Client can be frontend, user( basically who sends request)
 --It will take request from client and deliget them to respected classes.
 --But here it should know about all the objects to deligate and make it loosely coupled and client doesnt get in contact directly with other classes.
 --But doing this also breaks SRP and Principle of least Knowledge. So in some situations we need take a trade off




  